  "title": "可用性启发式：4 个最常用判断原则",
  "source": {
    "type": "article",
    "title": "可用性启发式：4 个最常用判断原则",
    "author": "Jakob Nielsen",
    "account": "Nielsen Norman Group",
    "accountOrDomain": "Nielsen Norman Group",
    "url": "https://www.nngroup.com/articles/ten-usability-heuristics/",
    "blocks": [
      {
        "id": "cn-guide-001",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "尼尔森的可用性启发式不是具体控件规范，而是一套帮助设计者判断界面问题的原则。本文节选的核心价值在于：用户需要知道系统正在发生什么，需要看到熟悉的语言和现实世界映射，需要能撤销或退出错误操作，也需要界面保持一致。阅读时不要把这些原则当成抽象口号，而要把它们放回具体情境中判断。例如，加载状态是否给了用户合理反馈，按钮命名是否符合用户心智，危险操作是否提供确认和恢复路径，不同页面的同类按钮是否位置一致。掌握这些原则后，学习者应该能解释一个界面为什么让人困惑，并能提出更具体的改进方向。"
      },
      {
        "id": "p-005",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The design should always keep users informed about what is going on, through appropriate feedback within a reasonable amount of time."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-006",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When users know the current system status, they learn the outcome of their prior interactions and determine next steps. Predictable interactions create trust in the product as well as the brand."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-011",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "You Are Here  indicators on mall maps show people where they currently are, to help them understand where to go next."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-013",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Communicate clearly to users what the system’s state is — no action with consequences to users should be taken without informing them."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-014",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Present feedback to the user as quickly as possible (ideally, immediately)."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-015",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Build trust through open and continuous communication ."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-020",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The design should speak the users' language. Use words, phrases, and concepts familiar to the user, rather than internal jargon. Follow real-world conventions, making information appear in a natural and logical order."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-021",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "The way you should design depends very much on your specific users. Terms, concepts, icons, and images that seem perfectly clear to you and your colleagues may be unfamiliar or confusing to your users."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-022",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When a design’s controls follow real-world conventions and correspond to desired outcomes (called natural mapping ), it’s easier for users to learn and remember how the interface works. This helps to build an experience that feels intuitive."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-024",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When stovetop controls match the layout of heating elements, users can quickly understand which control maps to which heating element."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-026",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Ensure that users can understand meaning without having to go look up a word’s definition."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-027",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Never assume your understanding of words or concepts will match that of your users."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-028",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "User research will uncover your users' familiar terminology, as well as their mental models around important concepts."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-033",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Users often perform actions by mistake. They need a clearly marked \"emergency exit\" to leave the unwanted action without having to go through an extended process."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-034",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "When it's easy for people to back out of a process or undo an action, it fosters a sense of freedom and confidence. Exits allow users to remain in control of the system and avoid getting stuck and feeling frustrated."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-036",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Digital spaces need quick emergency exits, just like physical spaces do."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-038",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Support Undo and Redo ."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-039",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Show a clear way to exit the current interaction, like a Cancel button ."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-040",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Make sure the exit is clearly labeled and discoverable."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-045",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Users should not have to wonder whether different words, situations, or actions mean the same thing. Follow platform and industry conventions."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-046",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Jakob's Law states that people spend most of their time using digital products other than yours . Users’ experiences with those other products set their expectations. Failing to maintain consistency may increase the users'  cognitive load by forcing them to learn something new."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-048",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Checkin counters are usually located at the front of hotels. This consistency meets customers’ expectations."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-050",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Improve learnability by maintaining both types of consistency: internal and external."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-051",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Maintain consistency  within a single product or a family of products (internal consistency)."
      },
      {
        "id": "p-052",
        "type": "paragraph",
        "text": "Follow established industry conventions (external consistency)."
      }
    ],
